04335nam a22005775i 9780889208803DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20062002xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97808892088037 a10.51644/97808892088032doi  a(DE-B1597)667333  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aB836.5b.B58 2002 7aSOC0220002bisacsh04a306/.012211 aBlack, J. David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Politics of Enchantment :bRomanticism, Media, and Cultural Studies /cJ. David Black. 1aWaterloo, Ontario : bWilfrid Laurier University Press, c[2006] 4c©2002  a1 online resource (210 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCultural Studies00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgements -- tThe Politics of Enchantment -- tThe Education of Desire -- tThe Secret Police at the Disco -- tThe Presence of the Past -- tThe Enemies of Love -- tInformation Wants to Be Free -- tThe Market in the Fallen World -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat do "raves" have to do with eighteenth-century Romanticism, or the latest communication technologies with historical ideas about language, media, and culture? Today’s culture dazzles us with technological marvels and media spectacles. While we find them entertaining, just as often they are troubling — they seem to contradict common sense, eliciting such questions as What is real? or What is reality? and What is language? or What does language do? These questions, once confined to scholars, have become everyone’s concern. Some of the best answers might be found in an unexpected source: Romanticism. Too often we bring the values of the Enlightenment, particularly that of reason, to critique phenomena not inherently rational, such as pop culture or the Internet. This means that much criticism of current culture already has an intellectual foundation antagonistic to it — inviting postmodern arguments that suggest history has ended and reality is an illusion. In contrast, Romanticism, a cultural movement founded in Germany and England during the late eighteenth century, offers us an archive of concepts surprisingly sensitive to these problems. The Romantics were poets, dreamers, and politicians who advanced ideas that anticipated much contemporary thinking. David Black has organized these ideas systematically, and has then applied them to key issues in communications, such as representation, audience, and the information society, as well as to significant debates in cultural studies. As a result, The Politics of Enchantment offers a new theory of media and culture that is grounded in intellectual history, yet as feverishly current as the latest digital device.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCulturexPhilosophy. 0aCulturexStudy and teaching. 0aMass media criticism. 0aMass mediaxPhilosophy. 0aRomanticism. 4aCultural Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Popular Culture.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978088920880340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780889208803423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780889208803/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles